Enumeration.DefinitionText: Sabotage: An act or acts with intent to injure, interfere with, or obstruct the national defence of a country by wilfully injuring or destroying, or attempting to injure or destroy, any national defence or war material, premises or utilities, to include human and natural resources.
Occupying: Moving onto an objective, key terrain, or other manmade or natural terrain area without opposition and controlling that entire area.
Governmental collapse: The sudden loss of force, effectiveness or authority of the governing organisation.
Crossing: Traversing a FEATURE or FACILITY.
Alert cancellation: The end of a state of readiness.
Setting up: Establishing a FACILITY, ORGANISATION or FEATURE.
Providing education services: Providing labour and materiel for the educational process.
Infiltration: Moving a force, broken down as individuals or small groups, over, through or around enemy positions with the aim of avoiding detection.

Demonstration: Conducting an offensive operation that is either an attack or a show of force on a front where a decision is not sought, made with the aim of deceiving the enemy. It is similar to a feint with the exception that no contact with the enemy is sought. In OOTW, an operation by military forces in sight of an actual or potential enemy to show military capabilities.
Canalise: Restricting operations to a narrow zone by use of existing or reinforcing obstacles or by fire or bombing.
Reconnaissance in force: Conducting an offensive operation designed to discover and/or test the enemys strength, or to obtain other information.
Massing of forces: The concentration of large quantities of military equipment and personnel.
Epidemic: A widespread occurrence of a disease in a community at a particular time.
Conducting sporting events: Conducting any game or competitive activity, especially an outdoor one involving physical exertion, e.g. cricket, football, racing, hunting.

Attack, main: Conducting the principal attack or effort into which the commander throws the full weight of the offensive power at his disposal. An attack directed against the chief objective of the campaign or battle.
Turning: Compelling an enemy force to move from one avenue of approach or movement corridor to another.
Robbery: Unlawfully taking property, valuables or money from a person or place.
Observing: Providing continuous view and the potential for reports on the activity of an object.
Genocide: The deliberated and systematic destruction of a racial, political or cultural group.
Crime against humanity: Violation of the laws so gross in numbers affected that it is considered to affect all humans and not only individuals.
Ambush: A surprise attack by fire or other destructive means from concealed positions on a moving or temporarily halted force or group of personnel.
Recuperating: Resting a unit after it has been in action. Some reconstitution may take place as well.
Military mobilisation: The act of assembling and making ready for active military service.
Escaping: Breaking free from a restriction or control of a place, person, or organisation.
Conducting forward passage of lines: Moving an incoming force through another force that is currently in contact with the enemy in order for the incoming force to come into contact with the enemy.
Attack, diversion: Conducting an attack wherein a force attacks, or threatens to attack, a target other than the main target for the purpose of drawing enemy defences away from the main effort.
Vandalism/Rape/Loot/Ransack/Plunder/Sack: An act of vandalism, raping, looting, ransacking or plundering against an individual or property.
Screening: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to observe, identify and report information, and which only fights in self-protection.
Offensive/counteroffensive: Conducting an operation by an attack force.
Guarding: Operating as a security element to protect the main body by fighting to gain time while also observing and reporting information.

Counter attack: Mounting an offensive operation in which an attack by a part or all of a defending force is made against an enemy attacking force, for such specific purposes as regaining ground lost, cutting off or destroying lead enemy units, and with the general objective of regaining the initiative and denying the enemy the attainment of his goal or purpose in attacking.
Airspace violation: The invasion of the declared own airspace by an aircraft.
Strafing, aerial: Attack by enemy aircraft against ground targets using forward firing ordnance (bullets, shells, or rockets).
Providing healthcare services: Providing labour and materiel for maintaining the general health and welfare.
Interception: Conducting electronic warfare support operations with a view to searching, locating and recording radiated electromagnetic energy.
Drug consumption, illegal: An action of consuming illegal drugs.
Bypass: Manoeuvring around an obstacle, position, or enemy force to maintain the momentum of advance.

Reconstituting: Attaining prescribed strength of units and prescribed levels of vehicles, equipment, stores and supplies. The process will only take place after a unit/formation combat effectiveness has been reduced.
Medical evacuation: The process of moving any person who is wounded, injured or ill to/between medical treatment FACILITYs.
Equipment failure: A cessation of proper functioning or performance of a piece of equipment.
Confiscation: The seizure of property under public authority.

Attack, electronic: Conducting electronic warfare involving the use of electromagnetic energy, directed energy or anti-radiation weapons to attack personnel, facilities, or equipment with the intent of degrading, neutralizing, or destroying enemy combat capability and is considered a form of fires.
UXO discovery: The detection of the presence of unexploded explosive ordnance.
Suicide: The action of killing oneself intentionally.
Providing infrastructure: Providing basic facilities such as roads, bridges, and sewers.
Intimidation: Act to frighten or overawe.
Drug manufacturing, illegal: An action to manufacture illegal drugs or to illegally manufacture legal drugs.
Avoiding: Staying clear of a specified object.
Recovering: Retrieving any lost, incapacitated or captured object.
Mine-laying: Emplacement or deployment of one or more mines.
Escorting: Accompanying and protecting another force or convoy.
Conducting preparatory fire: Delivering fire on a target preparatory to an assault.
Air assault: Mounting an assault utilising a mixture of aviation and ground transport, the principal feature of which is the insertion of combat power.
Verifying: Testifying to, asserting, affirming or confirming, as true or certain.
Security compromise: A release of information to someone unauthorised.
Organised crime: Violation of the laws of a civil society performed by a group of persons established for that reason.
Gunnery, air-to-air: The act of firing an air-to-air weapon, usually at an aircraft.
Counter-battery fire: Fire delivered for the purpose of destroying or neutralizing indirect fire weapons systems.
Carrier recovery: Aircraft recovery by a naval platform.
Strike: The organised refusal by employees to work until some grievance is remedied.

Providing host nation support: Providing civil and/or military assistance rendered by a nation to foreign forces within its territory during peacetime, crises or emergencies, or war based on agreements mutually concluded between nations.
Interdiction: Diverting, disrupting, delaying, or destroying the enemys surface military potential before it can be used effectively against friendly forces.
Drug distribution, illegal: An action to distribute illegal drugs or to illegally distribute legal drugs.
Booby trap discovery: The detection of a device intended to cause damage to unsuspecting people.
Securing: Gaining possession of a position or terrain feature, with or without force, and making such disposition to prevent, as far as possible, its destruction or loss by enemy action.
Peace treaty agreement: An arrangement or contract among involved nations or factions to end a conflict.
Attack, hasty: In land operations, an attack in which preparation time is traded for speed in order to exploit an opportunity.
Dazzle: Causing a temporary loss of vision or a temporary reduction in visual acuity; may also be applied to effects on optics.
Capture: Taking possession of an object, normally by force; it frequently involves movement as a preliminary phase.

Suppressing: Providing fires that neutralizes or temporarily degrades the capabilities of enemy forces within a specific area. This makes no assumptions as to enemy casualties; it may be a transitory effect.
Providing laundry services: Providing labour and materiel for laundering of clothes or linens.
Invasion: The act of taking possession of another land.
Drug operation: Illegal trafficking in drugs by a group or an organisation.

Attack, supporting: Conducting an offensive operation carried out in conjunction with a main attack and designed to achieve one or more of the following: a. deceive the enemy; b. destroy or pin down enemy forces which could interfere with the main attack; c. control ground whose occupation by the enemy will hinder the main attack; or d. force the enemy to commit reserves prematurely or in an indecisive area.
Redeployment: Transferring a unit, an individual, or supplies deployed in one area to another area, or to another location within the area, for the purpose of further employment.
Missing individual: The absence of a PERSON from an expected or anticipated location.
Evacuating: Clearing or removing materiel and personnel from a given locality.
Conducting road service: Enabling the movement of a number of specific units.
Amphibious operation: Mounting an operation launched from the sea by naval and land forces against a hostile, or potentially hostile shore.
Volcanic eruption: The release of lava or steam by a volcano.
Secession of portion of country: The formal withdrawal of a portion of a country.
Picketing: An act by a person or persons outside a place of work, intending to persuade esp. workers not to enter during a strike.
Harassing: Conducting an operation or executing a fire plan designed to curtail movement and, by threat of losses, to lower the morale of enemy troops.
Counter attack by fire: Denying the enemy his goal by using fire against an engagement area to defeat or destroy an enemy force.
Carrier launch: Launching of aircraft by a naval platform.
Serving as an in-place force: Operating as a force that provides fire and other support to the bridgehead force during an obstacle crossing.
Providing agricultural support: Providing advice or supplies for cultivating the soil and rearing animals.
Identifying: Determining the identification of a particular class of object, recognising the friendly or enemy character of an object, or detecting the presence of an object.
Massive deportation/banishment: The driving out or removing from a home or place of usual resort or continuance of a large number of people.
Attempted rape: The attempted act of forcing another person to submit to sexual intercourse.
Publishing press release: Making generally known an official statement issued to media for information.
Letter bomb explosion: The explosion of a seemingly harmless letter or parcel.
Election associated violence: The occurrence of violent acts due to an election process.
Clearing, radio net: Eliminating transmissions on a tactical radio net in order to allow a higher precedence transmission to occur.
Aerial shoot down: The deliberate destruction of an aircraft.
Troublemaking, inciting: Provoking to action, stirring up or urging on.
Revolution: The overthrow or renunciation of one government or ruler and the substitution of another by the governed.
Not otherwise specified: The appropriate value is not in the set of specified values.
Following and supporting: Operating as a committed force that follows and supports the mission accomplishment of a force conducting an offensive operation.

Containing: Restricting enemy forces by stopping, holding or surrounding them or compelling the enemy forces to centre activity on a given front and to prevent his withdrawing any part of his forces for use elsewhere.
Border incursion: Moving a force or a group of people across a national or territorial border.

Serving as a flank guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to protect the main force by fighting on the designated flank to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
Providing accommodation: Providing room for receiving people, esp. a place to live or lodgings.
Hunting: The activity of hunting wild animals or game, especially for food or sport.
Deploying: Moving to and adopting a tactical formation or dispersal at a specific location.
Attempted robbery: The attempted act of robbing a person or place.
Rocket fire: The employment of a rocket powered weapon.
Neutralize, combat: Rendering ineffective or unusable in military operations.
Firefighting: The activity of extinguishing fires.
Coup detat: A violent or illegal seizure of power.
Bombing, deliberate: A deliberate and intentional bombing incident.
Serving as a main body: Operating as the main force for a specific operation.
Providing bedding: Providing (1) sleeping accommodation or (2) mattress and bedclothes.
Illumination: Providing battlespace lighting by employing searchlight or pyrotechnic illuminants using diffusion or reflection.
Disease: A disorder of structure or function in a human, animal, or plant, especially one that produces specific symptoms or that affects a specific part.
Attempted murder: The attempted act of unlawfully killing of one human being by another, especially with premeditated malice.

Pursuing: Continuing an offensive operation in order to catch or cut off a hostile force attempting to escape, with the aim of destroying it. Typically, contact is maintained and risk taken to harass relentlessly, thereby turning the pursuit into a rout.
Letter bomb incident: The detection of a seemingly harmless letter or parcel.

Electronic warfare: Military action to exploit the electro-magnetic spectrum encompassing the search for, interception and identification of electro-magnetic emissions, the employment of electro-magnetic energy, including directed energy, to reduce or prevent hostile use of the electro-magnetic spectrum, and actions to ensure its effective use by friendly forces.
Conducting conference: Conducting a meeting for discussion, esp. a regular one held by an association or organisation.
Aerial engagement: The occurrence of a hostile encounter between military aircraft.
Troublemaking, intimidating: Discouraging or inhibiting by or as if by threats.
Riot: A disturbance of the peace by a crowd; an occurrence of public disorder.
Neutralize, chemical: Making safe or non-toxic an object contaminated with a chemical agent.
Forced landing: An aircraft that by hostile act, or lack of vital resources is compelled to land.
Bombing: Attacking, damaging or destroying through the use of bombs.
Rape: The act of forcing another person to submit to sexual intercourse.
Marking: Making visible (by the use of light/IR/laser/arty) an object in order to allow its identification by another object (usually as a precursor to the use of direct fire weapons).
Enemy contact: The situation when opposing forces are in sight of or in range of direct fire of each others weapons.
Conducting recreational activities: Conducting a refreshing or entertaining activity.
Breaching: Breaking through or securing a passage through an enemy defence, obstacle, minefield, or fortification.
Transporting: Moving assets to a specified objective by sea, land or air.

Relief in place: An operation in which, by direction of higher authority, all or part of a unit is replaced in an area by the incoming unit. The responsibilities of the replaced elements for the mission and the assigned zone of operations are transferred to the incoming unit. The incoming unit continues the operation as ordered.
Neutralize, explosive: Rendering bombs, mines, missiles, and booby traps into a safe state.
Friendly fire: Accidental damage by Allied troops to ones own installations, aircraft or personnel.

Covering: Operating as a force apart from the main body to protect the main body by fighting to gain time while also observing and reporting information and preventing enemy ground observation of an direct fire against the main body.
Attack, not otherwise specified: Conducting an offensive operation characterised by coordinated employment of firepower and manoeuvre to close with and destroy or capture the enemy.

Serving as a rear guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to move (or remain) at the rear of the main body and protect the main force by fighting to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
Providing camps: Providing temporary accommodation of various kinds, usually consisting of huts or tents, for detainees, homeless persons, and other emergency use.
Industrial espionage incident: The practice of spying or the use of spies to obtain information about the plans and activities of competitors.
Aircraft landing: The action of approaching and alighting on the ground or some other surface after a flight.
Outbreak of racial/tribal/ethnic warfare: The use of force or violence by or against racial or tribal groups.
Maintaining: Providing services to keep equipment in condition to carry out its function.
Engaging: Bringing the enemy under fire.
Conducting media interview: Conducting a conversation between a reporter etc. and a person of public interest, used as a basis of a broadcast or publication.
Burned out object: Complete destruction of an object by flames.
Treaty violation: An infringement or breaking of the provisions of a formal agreement.
State of war: A state characterised by hostile military activity between the parts.
Providing decontamination services: Providing purification of different items from contamination.
Indiscriminate shooting: Firing without a specific objective and without making distinction.
Attack, deliberate: Conducting an offensive operation characterised by pre-planned coordinated employment of firepower and manoeuvre to close with and destroy or capture the enemy.
Aircraft crash: The unforeseen destruction or damage of an aircraft (and personnel).

Reconnaissance: Conducting a mission to obtain by visual operations or other detection methods information about the activities and resources of an enemy or potential enemy, or to secure data concerning the meteorological, hydrographic or geographic characteristics of a particular area.
Martial law implementation: Giving practical effect to military law, usually by restricting the rights of citizens for security reasons.
Enveloping: Manoeuvring by the main attacking force to pass around or over the enemys principal defensive positions with the aim of securing objectives to the enemys rear.
Conducting social events: Conducting any social gathering, esp. one organised by a club or congregation.
Border raid: A surprise attack by a force or a group of people across a national or territorial border (restricted to 25 km from the border).
Traversing: Travelling over a designated route.
Rendezvous: Achieving a pre-arranged meeting at a given time and place.
Obscure: Covering something by a smoke screen.
Generating chemical smoke: Producing chemical smoke to act as a form of cover to protect ongoing operations.
Criminal incident: A violation of law.
Attempted suicide: The attempted act of killing oneself intentionally.
Serving as a reserve: Operating as a force that may be committed into combat only on the order of the commander of the organisation who so designated the reserve force.
Providing construction services: Providing labour and materiel for construction of facilities.
Indirect fire: Fire delivered on a target that is not itself used as a point of aim for the weapons or the director.
Diversion: Drawing the attention and forces of an enemy from the point of the principal operation; an attack, alarm, or feint that diverts attention.
Aircraft launch activity: The occurrence of one or more aircraft taking off.
Torture: An action or practice of inflicting severe pain as a punishment or a forcible means of persuasion.
Pestilence: A fatal epidemic disease, especially bubonic plague.
Labour strike: The organised refusal by employees to work until some grievance is remedied.
Civil unrest: A behaviour that results in the disturbance of the normal order of society that generally falls short of riots and/or property destruction in the civil population.
Destroying: Physically rendering an enemy force combat-ineffective or damaging a target so that it cannot function as intended, nor be restored to a usable condition without being entirely rebuilt.
Build-up: Attaining prescribed strength of units and prescribed levels of vehicles, equipment, stores and supplies.
Repairing: Restoring an item to serviceable condition through correction of a specific failure or unserviceable condition.
National election: An ACTION-EVENT in which national officials are selected by vote.
Fix, acoustic: Determining a position using acoustic data.
Communications disruption: Interruption of the passage of communications by natural or man-made phenomena.
Assembling: Joining together of multiple objects in the same area.
Witnessing: Observing an activity that may result in the need to provide evidence.
Space accident: The unforeseen loss, destruction or damage of a spacecraft.
Political execution: A putting to death of a person or group of persons for political reasons.
Hold, defensive: Maintaining or retaining possession by force a position or area in defensive operations.
Defending: Protecting a defined object against an enemy attack.
Accident, weapon: An accident involving a weapon.
Threaten: Menacing an armed force by manoeuvre or action.
Proxy-bombing: A deliberate and intentional bombing incident that happens unexpectedly where the perpetrator acts through a representative.
Kidnapping: Seizing and holding a person unlawfully, usually for ransom or political gain.
Civil demonstration, legal: A public meeting or march legally expressing protest or other opinion on an issue.
Distributing: Dividing or dispensing in portions.
Blocking: Denying of enemy access to an area or preventing his advance in a direction or along an avenue of approach.

Serving as an advance guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to move ahead of the main body and protect the main force by fighting to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
POW return: The arrival of a POW or a group of POWs to their own forces or country.
National holiday: A day designated by a national authority as a day when work is not compulsory.

Delaying: Slowing the momentum of the enemy by conducting an operation in which the force under pressure trades time for space; the aim is to inflict the maximum damage on the enemy without becoming decisively engaged.
Accident, mine: An accident involving unexploded ordnance.
Troublemaking, agitating: Stirring up of public interest on a matter of controversy, such as a political or social issue.

Psychological operation: Planned operations to convey selected information and indicators to foreign audiences to influence their emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behaviour of foreign governments, organisations, groups, and individuals. The purpose of psychological operations is to induce or reinforce foreign attitudes and behaviour favourable to the originators objectives.
Death, natural causes: Normal termination of life.
Leaguer: Adopting a defended formation as a temporary defensive measure in areas of low or moderate risk of combat.
Civil war: A war among fellow-citizens or within the limits of one community.
Border crossing, surveilled: A border crossing that is conducted under surveillance.
Resupplying: Replenishing stocks in order to maintain the required levels of supply.
National state of emergency: A political term, to describe a condition approximating to that of war, wherein the normal constitution is suspended.
Fix, electromagnetic: Determining a position using electromagnetic data.
Communications interception: Capturing electromagnetic communications signals.
Artillery fire: The use of artillery fire.
Weapon firing: The firing of weapons.
Spying: Obtaining intelligence information furtively as an agent of a foreign power or competition.
Prisoner exchange: The act of giving or taking POWs in return for others.
Hold, offensive: Exerting sufficient pressure by means of combat power in an attack to prevent the movement or redeployment of enemy forces.
Deflecting: Preventing an enemy force from following the intended course.
Accident, traffic: An accident involving at least one motor vehicle.
Retain: Occupying and holding a terrain feature to ensure it is free of enemy occupation or use.
Naval platform flight operations: Aircraft launch or recovery by a naval platform.
Flood: The overflowing of a body of water onto dry land.
Communications restoration: The reestablishment of the ability to communicate.
Aircraft loss: The unforeseen loss of an aircraft (and personnel), other than crash.

Serving as a bridgehead force: Operating as a force that seizes or controls ground in order to permit the continuous embarkation, landing or crossing of troops or materiel and to provide manoeuvre space during a water obstacle crossing.
Procuring: Buying whatever is needed to fulfil a certain action.
Human rights violation: The commitment of an act against human rights.
Demolition: The destruction of structures, facilities, or materiel by use of fire, water, explosives, mechanical, or other means.
Bombing, accidental: An unfortunate bombing incident that happens unexpectedly and unintentionally.
Troublemaking, bullying: Intimidating by the use of superior size or strength.
Local election: An ACTION-EVENT in which local officials are selected by vote.
Patrolling: Gathering information or carrying out a destructive, harassing, mopping-up, or security mission.
Earthquake: A convulsion of the earths crust due to the release of accumulated stress as a result of faults in strata or volcanic action.
Clearing, air: Clearing of the air to gain either temporary or permanent air superiority or control in a given sector.
Atmospheric pollution: Contamination of the atmosphere caused by a poison or toxin.
Resting: Observing a specified period of inactivity by an organisation that is out of contact with the enemy.
Naval gun fire: The act of firing a naval surface-to-surface weapon.
Fix, electro-optical: Determining a position using electro-optical data.
Communications outage: The failure of communications equipment due to a mechanical malfunction.
Advancing: Moving towards an objective in some form of tactical formation. This is a transitional phase between operations that may or may not result in contact with the enemy.
Publishing media documentary: Making generally known any document published on a media that provides a factual record or report.
Troublemaking, hooliganism: Causing difficulties by the actions of hoodlums, especially young ruffians.
Looting: Act to take private property from an enemy in war or stolen by thieves.
Electronic emission: The radiation of electromagnetic energy.
Clearing, obstacle: Eliminating or neutralizing an obstacle.
Assassination: Murder of a prominent person.
Retire: Moving a force out of contact with the enemy with the expectation of no further significant contact.
Network seizure: Taking electronic control of a communications network.

Following and assuming: Operating as a committed force that is following a force conducting an offensive operation and is prepared to continue the mission of the force it is following when that force is fixed, attrited, or otherwise unable to continue.
Constructing: Building, digging or creating an object.
Accident, workplace: An accident occurring at the workplace.
Serving as a breakout force: Operating as a force that is tasked with the continuation of the operation during an obstacle crossing.
Protection, electronic: That division of electronic warfare involving actions taken to ensure effective friendly use of the electromagnetic spectrum despite the enemys use of electromagnetic energy.
Hostage taking: Action to seize or hold a person as security for the fulfilment of a condition.
Denying: Preventing access by blocking, disrupting, dislocating and/or bringing fire to bear.
Belly landing: An aircraft has landed without using the landing gear.
Troublemaking, harassing: Persecuting systematically by besetting with annoyances, threats or demands.
Locating: Establishing the position of an object.
Publishing media article: Making generally known a non-fictional essay, especially one included with others in a newspaper, magazine, journal, etc.
Early warning alert: Early notification of the launch or approach of weapons or weapons carriers.
Clearing, land combat: Removing all enemy forces from a specific location, area, or zone.
Assisting a criminal: Assisting or abetting a known criminal or terrorist.
Reinforcing: Making a force available for the purpose of supplementing an in-place force.
Explosion: A sudden release of any kind of energy.
Consolidating of a position: Re-organising and strengthening of a newly captured position so that it can be used against the enemy.
Codeword execution: Initiating the codeword activity.
War/military conference: A meeting of a group of persons to discuss war/military process.
Security violation: An infringement of a security protocol.
Peace conference: A meeting of a group of persons to discuss a peace process.

Deception, electronic: In electronic countermeasures, the deliberate radiation, re-radiation, alteration, absorption or reflection of electromagnetic energy in a manner intended to confuse, distract or seduce an enemy or his electronic systems.
Border crossing, forced: A border crossing that is conducted under pressure.
Supporting: Aiding, protecting, complementing or sustaining an object.
Providing repair services: Providing labour and materiel to restore objects to sound condition.

Isolation: Sealing off (both physically and psychologically) an enemy from its sources of support, denying an enemy freedom of movement, and preventing an enemy unit from having contact with other enemy forces.
Drug storage: An action to store drugs.
Arms trade: A happening of selling or buying of arms.
Refugee movement: The movement of people who has been forced to leave their country in order to escape war, persecution, or natural disaster.
Mission staging: The assembly of aircraft for the completion of a mission or other activity.
Execution: Putting a person to death, especially as a legal penalty.
Conducting rearward passage of lines: Moving a force through the defensive positions of another force behind it in order to break contact with the enemy.
Ceremony or parade: The formal gathering of a group of people in order to carry out an act or series of acts prescribed by ritual protocol or convention.
Abdication: The renouncement by a person of his official functions.
War/crisis alert: The state of readiness caused by the possibility of a war.
Surveillance, electronic: The systematic observation of aerospace, surface or subsurface areas, places, persons, or things, by electronic means.
Issuing media documentary: Sending forth or putting into circulation any document published on a media that provides a factual record or report.
Drought: A prolonged or chronic shortage of water.

Airborne assault: Mounting an airborne operation, a phase beginning with delivery by air of the assault echelon of the force into the objective area and extending through attack of assault objectives and consolidation of the initial airhead.
Religious demonstration: A public display of group feelings towards a religious idea, person or cause.
Mortar fire: The discharge of a projectile from a mortar weapon.

Exploitation: Taking advantage of a successful attack by mounting an offensive operation to follow-up and harass a dislocated enemy with the aim of further disorganising him in depth. This may provide the opportunity to capture ground that was not part of the objective of the original attack.
Collision, mid-air: In-flight collision of an aircraft with another aircraft.
CBRN-EVENT: An ACTION-EVENT that involves chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear materiel individually or in combination.
War crime: Violation of the laws and customs of war, i.e. the principles and norms of international law that enshrine the rights and duties of warring parties and neutral states.
Seizing: Clearing a designated area and obtaining control of it.
Penetrating: Breaking through the enemys defence or disrupting the enemys defensive systems.
Hijacking, not otherwise specified: Seizure of a vehicle in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Deception: Employing measures designed to mislead the enemy by manipulation, distortion, or falsification of evidence to induce him to react in a manner prejudicial to his interests.
Border crossing, escorted: A border crossing that is conducted under escort.
Surrender: Yielding to the control or power of the enemy.
Providing security services: Providing labour and materiel to assure safety of personnel and facilities.
Issuing media article: Sending forth or putting into circulation a non-fictional essay, especially one included with others in a newspaper, magazine, or journal.
Drug transportation: An action to transport drugs.
Arms production: An activity of, relating to or based on the production of arms.
Vessel sinking: The unforeseen loss, damage or destruction of a vessel by submersion.
Poisoning: Injuring or killing with toxic agents.
Hijacking, land vehicle: Seizure of a land vehicle in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Arresting/obstructing: Stopping or checking of the motion, progress, growth, or spread of something.
Suspension of hostilities: The cessation of war activities.
Providing storage services: Providing services for storage.
Issuing press release: Sending forth or putting into circulation an official statement issued to media for information.
Drive-by shooting: The act of firing a weapon, usually at a person, from a passing vehicle.
Accident: An unfortunate event, esp. one causing physical harm or damage, brought about unintentionally.
Civil demonstration, illegal: A public meeting or march illegally expressing protest or other opinion on an issue.
Religious violence: Individual or organised act directed against groups or individuals because of their religious beliefs.
Murder: The unlawful killing of one human being by another, especially with premeditated malice.
Famine: An extreme scarcity of food.
Collision, obstacle: In-flight collision of an aircraft with natural or man-made object (fixed or mobile) located on the ground.
Border crossing, planned: A border crossing that is known to have been planned ahead of time.
Oceans, seas or water pollution: Contamination of a body of water caused by a poison or toxin.
Shooting: The act of firing of a weapon, usually at a person.
Petroleum product spills: The accidental or delivered release of any petroleum product into the environment.
Hijacking, boat: Seizure of a boat or ship in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Death of chief of state: Self-defined.
Arson: The crime of maliciously setting fire to the property of another or of burning ones own property for an improper purpose, as to collect insurance.
Reorganising: Changing a task organisation for a particular operation. (Normally takes place before an operation). This includes the transfer of authority.
Natural disaster: The damage caused by force of nature, such as a hurricane, cyclone, tornado or tidal wave.
Fix: Preventing the enemy from moving any part of his force from a specific location for a specific period of time.
Communications deactivation: The disabling of transmission of information.
Border crossing, illegal: A border crossing that is forbidden by law.
Withdrawal: Disengaging a force in contact from an enemy force.
Sniper attack: An attack by one who shoots at others from a concealed place.
Political demonstration: A public display of group feelings towards a political idea, person or cause.
Hijacking, plane: Seizure of an aircraft in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Defeat: Diminution of the effectiveness of the enemy to the extent that he is unable to participate further in the battle or at least cannot fulfil his intention.
Arresting, legal: Seizing and detaining of a person under authority of the law.

Terrorism: Using or threatening force or violence against individuals or property in an attempt to coerce or intimidate governments or societies to achieve political, religious or ideological objectives.
Providing transhipment services: Providing movement of cargo from one ship or train or container to another for further shipment.
Jamming: Deliberately radiating, re-radiating or reflecting electromagnetic energy with the object of impairing the use of electronic devices, equipment or systems being used by the enemy.

Disrupting: Breaking apart an enemys formation and tempo, interrupting the enemys time table, causing premature commitment of forces, and/or splintering their attack using integrated fire planning and obstacle effect.
Civil disobedience: The refusal to comply with certain laws or to pay taxes etc. as a peaceful form of political protest.
Accident, aircraft ground: An accident involving an aircraft during ground operations or maintenance.
Religious warfare: An act of open armed conflict due to a difference of religious belief between two separate groups.
Mutual assistance pact agreement: An arrangement or contract between a number of organisations to provide mutual support.
Fire: A rapid, persistent chemical reaction that releases heat and light, especially the exothermic combination of a combustible substance with oxygen.
Communications activation: The enabling of transmission of information.
Border crossing, not-planned: A border crossing that is unplanned.
Withdrawal under pressure: Disengaging from the enemy when the enemy has sufficient contact with friendly forces to interfere with the withdrawal.

Datatype.DefinitionText: A data type for a designator for a name which denotes the category that some event falls under.

Enumeration.DefinitionText: Sabotage: An act or acts with intent to injure, interfere with, or obstruct the national defence of a country by wilfully injuring or destroying, or attempting to injure or destroy, any national defence or war material, premises or utilities, to include human and natural resources.
Occupying: Moving onto an objective, key terrain, or other manmade or natural terrain area without opposition and controlling that entire area.
Governmental collapse: The sudden loss of force, effectiveness or authority of the governing organisation.
Crossing: Traversing a FEATURE or FACILITY.
Alert cancellation: The end of a state of readiness.
Setting up: Establishing a FACILITY, ORGANISATION or FEATURE.
Providing education services: Providing labour and materiel for the educational process.
Infiltration: Moving a force, broken down as individuals or small groups, over, through or around enemy positions with the aim of avoiding detection.

Demonstration: Conducting an offensive operation that is either an attack or a show of force on a front where a decision is not sought, made with the aim of deceiving the enemy. It is similar to a feint with the exception that no contact with the enemy is sought. In OOTW, an operation by military forces in sight of an actual or potential enemy to show military capabilities.
Canalise: Restricting operations to a narrow zone by use of existing or reinforcing obstacles or by fire or bombing.
Reconnaissance in force: Conducting an offensive operation designed to discover and/or test the enemys strength, or to obtain other information.
Massing of forces: The concentration of large quantities of military equipment and personnel.
Epidemic: A widespread occurrence of a disease in a community at a particular time.
Conducting sporting events: Conducting any game or competitive activity, especially an outdoor one involving physical exertion, e.g. cricket, football, racing, hunting.

Attack, main: Conducting the principal attack or effort into which the commander throws the full weight of the offensive power at his disposal. An attack directed against the chief objective of the campaign or battle.
Turning: Compelling an enemy force to move from one avenue of approach or movement corridor to another.
Robbery: Unlawfully taking property, valuables or money from a person or place.
Observing: Providing continuous view and the potential for reports on the activity of an object.
Genocide: The deliberated and systematic destruction of a racial, political or cultural group.
Crime against humanity: Violation of the laws so gross in numbers affected that it is considered to affect all humans and not only individuals.
Ambush: A surprise attack by fire or other destructive means from concealed positions on a moving or temporarily halted force or group of personnel.
Recuperating: Resting a unit after it has been in action. Some reconstitution may take place as well.
Military mobilisation: The act of assembling and making ready for active military service.
Escaping: Breaking free from a restriction or control of a place, person, or organisation.
Conducting forward passage of lines: Moving an incoming force through another force that is currently in contact with the enemy in order for the incoming force to come into contact with the enemy.
Attack, diversion: Conducting an attack wherein a force attacks, or threatens to attack, a target other than the main target for the purpose of drawing enemy defences away from the main effort.
Vandalism/Rape/Loot/Ransack/Plunder/Sack: An act of vandalism, raping, looting, ransacking or plundering against an individual or property.
Screening: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to observe, identify and report information, and which only fights in self-protection.
Offensive/counteroffensive: Conducting an operation by an attack force.
Guarding: Operating as a security element to protect the main body by fighting to gain time while also observing and reporting information.

Counter attack: Mounting an offensive operation in which an attack by a part or all of a defending force is made against an enemy attacking force, for such specific purposes as regaining ground lost, cutting off or destroying lead enemy units, and with the general objective of regaining the initiative and denying the enemy the attainment of his goal or purpose in attacking.
Airspace violation: The invasion of the declared own airspace by an aircraft.
Strafing, aerial: Attack by enemy aircraft against ground targets using forward firing ordnance (bullets, shells, or rockets).
Providing healthcare services: Providing labour and materiel for maintaining the general health and welfare.
Interception: Conducting electronic warfare support operations with a view to searching, locating and recording radiated electromagnetic energy.
Drug consumption, illegal: An action of consuming illegal drugs.
Bypass: Manoeuvring around an obstacle, position, or enemy force to maintain the momentum of advance.

Reconstituting: Attaining prescribed strength of units and prescribed levels of vehicles, equipment, stores and supplies. The process will only take place after a unit/formation combat effectiveness has been reduced.
Medical evacuation: The process of moving any person who is wounded, injured or ill to/between medical treatment FACILITYs.
Equipment failure: A cessation of proper functioning or performance of a piece of equipment.
Confiscation: The seizure of property under public authority.

Attack, electronic: Conducting electronic warfare involving the use of electromagnetic energy, directed energy or anti-radiation weapons to attack personnel, facilities, or equipment with the intent of degrading, neutralizing, or destroying enemy combat capability and is considered a form of fires.
UXO discovery: The detection of the presence of unexploded explosive ordnance.
Suicide: The action of killing oneself intentionally.
Providing infrastructure: Providing basic facilities such as roads, bridges, and sewers.
Intimidation: Act to frighten or overawe.
Drug manufacturing, illegal: An action to manufacture illegal drugs or to illegally manufacture legal drugs.
Avoiding: Staying clear of a specified object.
Recovering: Retrieving any lost, incapacitated or captured object.
Mine-laying: Emplacement or deployment of one or more mines.
Escorting: Accompanying and protecting another force or convoy.
Conducting preparatory fire: Delivering fire on a target preparatory to an assault.
Air assault: Mounting an assault utilising a mixture of aviation and ground transport, the principal feature of which is the insertion of combat power.
Verifying: Testifying to, asserting, affirming or confirming, as true or certain.
Security compromise: A release of information to someone unauthorised.
Organised crime: Violation of the laws of a civil society performed by a group of persons established for that reason.
Gunnery, air-to-air: The act of firing an air-to-air weapon, usually at an aircraft.
Counter-battery fire: Fire delivered for the purpose of destroying or neutralizing indirect fire weapons systems.
Carrier recovery: Aircraft recovery by a naval platform.
Strike: The organised refusal by employees to work until some grievance is remedied.

Providing host nation support: Providing civil and/or military assistance rendered by a nation to foreign forces within its territory during peacetime, crises or emergencies, or war based on agreements mutually concluded between nations.
Interdiction: Diverting, disrupting, delaying, or destroying the enemys surface military potential before it can be used effectively against friendly forces.
Drug distribution, illegal: An action to distribute illegal drugs or to illegally distribute legal drugs.
Booby trap discovery: The detection of a device intended to cause damage to unsuspecting people.
Securing: Gaining possession of a position or terrain feature, with or without force, and making such disposition to prevent, as far as possible, its destruction or loss by enemy action.
Peace treaty agreement: An arrangement or contract among involved nations or factions to end a conflict.
Attack, hasty: In land operations, an attack in which preparation time is traded for speed in order to exploit an opportunity.
Dazzle: Causing a temporary loss of vision or a temporary reduction in visual acuity; may also be applied to effects on optics.
Capture: Taking possession of an object, normally by force; it frequently involves movement as a preliminary phase.

Suppressing: Providing fires that neutralizes or temporarily degrades the capabilities of enemy forces within a specific area. This makes no assumptions as to enemy casualties; it may be a transitory effect.
Providing laundry services: Providing labour and materiel for laundering of clothes or linens.
Invasion: The act of taking possession of another land.
Drug operation: Illegal trafficking in drugs by a group or an organisation.

Attack, supporting: Conducting an offensive operation carried out in conjunction with a main attack and designed to achieve one or more of the following: a. deceive the enemy; b. destroy or pin down enemy forces which could interfere with the main attack; c. control ground whose occupation by the enemy will hinder the main attack; or d. force the enemy to commit reserves prematurely or in an indecisive area.
Redeployment: Transferring a unit, an individual, or supplies deployed in one area to another area, or to another location within the area, for the purpose of further employment.
Missing individual: The absence of a PERSON from an expected or anticipated location.
Evacuating: Clearing or removing materiel and personnel from a given locality.
Conducting road service: Enabling the movement of a number of specific units.
Amphibious operation: Mounting an operation launched from the sea by naval and land forces against a hostile, or potentially hostile shore.
Volcanic eruption: The release of lava or steam by a volcano.
Secession of portion of country: The formal withdrawal of a portion of a country.
Picketing: An act by a person or persons outside a place of work, intending to persuade esp. workers not to enter during a strike.
Harassing: Conducting an operation or executing a fire plan designed to curtail movement and, by threat of losses, to lower the morale of enemy troops.
Counter attack by fire: Denying the enemy his goal by using fire against an engagement area to defeat or destroy an enemy force.
Carrier launch: Launching of aircraft by a naval platform.
Serving as an in-place force: Operating as a force that provides fire and other support to the bridgehead force during an obstacle crossing.
Providing agricultural support: Providing advice or supplies for cultivating the soil and rearing animals.
Identifying: Determining the identification of a particular class of object, recognising the friendly or enemy character of an object, or detecting the presence of an object.
Massive deportation/banishment: The driving out or removing from a home or place of usual resort or continuance of a large number of people.
Attempted rape: The attempted act of forcing another person to submit to sexual intercourse.
Publishing press release: Making generally known an official statement issued to media for information.
Letter bomb explosion: The explosion of a seemingly harmless letter or parcel.
Election associated violence: The occurrence of violent acts due to an election process.
Clearing, radio net: Eliminating transmissions on a tactical radio net in order to allow a higher precedence transmission to occur.
Aerial shoot down: The deliberate destruction of an aircraft.
Troublemaking, inciting: Provoking to action, stirring up or urging on.
Revolution: The overthrow or renunciation of one government or ruler and the substitution of another by the governed.
Not otherwise specified: The appropriate value is not in the set of specified values.
Following and supporting: Operating as a committed force that follows and supports the mission accomplishment of a force conducting an offensive operation.

Containing: Restricting enemy forces by stopping, holding or surrounding them or compelling the enemy forces to centre activity on a given front and to prevent his withdrawing any part of his forces for use elsewhere.
Border incursion: Moving a force or a group of people across a national or territorial border.

Serving as a flank guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to protect the main force by fighting on the designated flank to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
Providing accommodation: Providing room for receiving people, esp. a place to live or lodgings.
Hunting: The activity of hunting wild animals or game, especially for food or sport.
Deploying: Moving to and adopting a tactical formation or dispersal at a specific location.
Attempted robbery: The attempted act of robbing a person or place.
Rocket fire: The employment of a rocket powered weapon.
Neutralize, combat: Rendering ineffective or unusable in military operations.
Firefighting: The activity of extinguishing fires.
Coup detat: A violent or illegal seizure of power.
Bombing, deliberate: A deliberate and intentional bombing incident.
Serving as a main body: Operating as the main force for a specific operation.
Providing bedding: Providing (1) sleeping accommodation or (2) mattress and bedclothes.
Illumination: Providing battlespace lighting by employing searchlight or pyrotechnic illuminants using diffusion or reflection.
Disease: A disorder of structure or function in a human, animal, or plant, especially one that produces specific symptoms or that affects a specific part.
Attempted murder: The attempted act of unlawfully killing of one human being by another, especially with premeditated malice.

Pursuing: Continuing an offensive operation in order to catch or cut off a hostile force attempting to escape, with the aim of destroying it. Typically, contact is maintained and risk taken to harass relentlessly, thereby turning the pursuit into a rout.
Letter bomb incident: The detection of a seemingly harmless letter or parcel.

Electronic warfare: Military action to exploit the electro-magnetic spectrum encompassing the search for, interception and identification of electro-magnetic emissions, the employment of electro-magnetic energy, including directed energy, to reduce or prevent hostile use of the electro-magnetic spectrum, and actions to ensure its effective use by friendly forces.
Conducting conference: Conducting a meeting for discussion, esp. a regular one held by an association or organisation.
Aerial engagement: The occurrence of a hostile encounter between military aircraft.
Troublemaking, intimidating: Discouraging or inhibiting by or as if by threats.
Riot: A disturbance of the peace by a crowd; an occurrence of public disorder.
Neutralize, chemical: Making safe or non-toxic an object contaminated with a chemical agent.
Forced landing: An aircraft that by hostile act, or lack of vital resources is compelled to land.
Bombing: Attacking, damaging or destroying through the use of bombs.
Rape: The act of forcing another person to submit to sexual intercourse.
Marking: Making visible (by the use of light/IR/laser/arty) an object in order to allow its identification by another object (usually as a precursor to the use of direct fire weapons).
Enemy contact: The situation when opposing forces are in sight of or in range of direct fire of each others weapons.
Conducting recreational activities: Conducting a refreshing or entertaining activity.
Breaching: Breaking through or securing a passage through an enemy defence, obstacle, minefield, or fortification.
Transporting: Moving assets to a specified objective by sea, land or air.

Relief in place: An operation in which, by direction of higher authority, all or part of a unit is replaced in an area by the incoming unit. The responsibilities of the replaced elements for the mission and the assigned zone of operations are transferred to the incoming unit. The incoming unit continues the operation as ordered.
Neutralize, explosive: Rendering bombs, mines, missiles, and booby traps into a safe state.
Friendly fire: Accidental damage by Allied troops to ones own installations, aircraft or personnel.

Covering: Operating as a force apart from the main body to protect the main body by fighting to gain time while also observing and reporting information and preventing enemy ground observation of an direct fire against the main body.
Attack, not otherwise specified: Conducting an offensive operation characterised by coordinated employment of firepower and manoeuvre to close with and destroy or capture the enemy.

Serving as a rear guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to move (or remain) at the rear of the main body and protect the main force by fighting to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
Providing camps: Providing temporary accommodation of various kinds, usually consisting of huts or tents, for detainees, homeless persons, and other emergency use.
Industrial espionage incident: The practice of spying or the use of spies to obtain information about the plans and activities of competitors.
Aircraft landing: The action of approaching and alighting on the ground or some other surface after a flight.
Outbreak of racial/tribal/ethnic warfare: The use of force or violence by or against racial or tribal groups.
Maintaining: Providing services to keep equipment in condition to carry out its function.
Engaging: Bringing the enemy under fire.
Conducting media interview: Conducting a conversation between a reporter etc. and a person of public interest, used as a basis of a broadcast or publication.
Burned out object: Complete destruction of an object by flames.
Treaty violation: An infringement or breaking of the provisions of a formal agreement.
State of war: A state characterised by hostile military activity between the parts.
Providing decontamination services: Providing purification of different items from contamination.
Indiscriminate shooting: Firing without a specific objective and without making distinction.
Attack, deliberate: Conducting an offensive operation characterised by pre-planned coordinated employment of firepower and manoeuvre to close with and destroy or capture the enemy.
Aircraft crash: The unforeseen destruction or damage of an aircraft (and personnel).

Reconnaissance: Conducting a mission to obtain by visual operations or other detection methods information about the activities and resources of an enemy or potential enemy, or to secure data concerning the meteorological, hydrographic or geographic characteristics of a particular area.
Martial law implementation: Giving practical effect to military law, usually by restricting the rights of citizens for security reasons.
Enveloping: Manoeuvring by the main attacking force to pass around or over the enemys principal defensive positions with the aim of securing objectives to the enemys rear.
Conducting social events: Conducting any social gathering, esp. one organised by a club or congregation.
Border raid: A surprise attack by a force or a group of people across a national or territorial border (restricted to 25 km from the border).
Traversing: Travelling over a designated route.
Rendezvous: Achieving a pre-arranged meeting at a given time and place.
Obscure: Covering something by a smoke screen.
Generating chemical smoke: Producing chemical smoke to act as a form of cover to protect ongoing operations.
Criminal incident: A violation of law.
Attempted suicide: The attempted act of killing oneself intentionally.
Serving as a reserve: Operating as a force that may be committed into combat only on the order of the commander of the organisation who so designated the reserve force.
Providing construction services: Providing labour and materiel for construction of facilities.
Indirect fire: Fire delivered on a target that is not itself used as a point of aim for the weapons or the director.
Diversion: Drawing the attention and forces of an enemy from the point of the principal operation; an attack, alarm, or feint that diverts attention.
Aircraft launch activity: The occurrence of one or more aircraft taking off.
Torture: An action or practice of inflicting severe pain as a punishment or a forcible means of persuasion.
Pestilence: A fatal epidemic disease, especially bubonic plague.
Labour strike: The organised refusal by employees to work until some grievance is remedied.
Civil unrest: A behaviour that results in the disturbance of the normal order of society that generally falls short of riots and/or property destruction in the civil population.
Destroying: Physically rendering an enemy force combat-ineffective or damaging a target so that it cannot function as intended, nor be restored to a usable condition without being entirely rebuilt.
Build-up: Attaining prescribed strength of units and prescribed levels of vehicles, equipment, stores and supplies.
Repairing: Restoring an item to serviceable condition through correction of a specific failure or unserviceable condition.
National election: An ACTION-EVENT in which national officials are selected by vote.
Fix, acoustic: Determining a position using acoustic data.
Communications disruption: Interruption of the passage of communications by natural or man-made phenomena.
Assembling: Joining together of multiple objects in the same area.
Witnessing: Observing an activity that may result in the need to provide evidence.
Space accident: The unforeseen loss, destruction or damage of a spacecraft.
Political execution: A putting to death of a person or group of persons for political reasons.
Hold, defensive: Maintaining or retaining possession by force a position or area in defensive operations.
Defending: Protecting a defined object against an enemy attack.
Accident, weapon: An accident involving a weapon.
Threaten: Menacing an armed force by manoeuvre or action.
Proxy-bombing: A deliberate and intentional bombing incident that happens unexpectedly where the perpetrator acts through a representative.
Kidnapping: Seizing and holding a person unlawfully, usually for ransom or political gain.
Civil demonstration, legal: A public meeting or march legally expressing protest or other opinion on an issue.
Distributing: Dividing or dispensing in portions.
Blocking: Denying of enemy access to an area or preventing his advance in a direction or along an avenue of approach.

Serving as an advance guard: Operating as a security element whose primary task is to move ahead of the main body and protect the main force by fighting to gain time, whilst also observing and reporting information.
POW return: The arrival of a POW or a group of POWs to their own forces or country.
National holiday: A day designated by a national authority as a day when work is not compulsory.

Delaying: Slowing the momentum of the enemy by conducting an operation in which the force under pressure trades time for space; the aim is to inflict the maximum damage on the enemy without becoming decisively engaged.
Accident, mine: An accident involving unexploded ordnance.
Troublemaking, agitating: Stirring up of public interest on a matter of controversy, such as a political or social issue.

Psychological operation: Planned operations to convey selected information and indicators to foreign audiences to influence their emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behaviour of foreign governments, organisations, groups, and individuals. The purpose of psychological operations is to induce or reinforce foreign attitudes and behaviour favourable to the originators objectives.
Death, natural causes: Normal termination of life.
Leaguer: Adopting a defended formation as a temporary defensive measure in areas of low or moderate risk of combat.
Civil war: A war among fellow-citizens or within the limits of one community.
Border crossing, surveilled: A border crossing that is conducted under surveillance.
Resupplying: Replenishing stocks in order to maintain the required levels of supply.
National state of emergency: A political term, to describe a condition approximating to that of war, wherein the normal constitution is suspended.
Fix, electromagnetic: Determining a position using electromagnetic data.
Communications interception: Capturing electromagnetic communications signals.
Artillery fire: The use of artillery fire.
Weapon firing: The firing of weapons.
Spying: Obtaining intelligence information furtively as an agent of a foreign power or competition.
Prisoner exchange: The act of giving or taking POWs in return for others.
Hold, offensive: Exerting sufficient pressure by means of combat power in an attack to prevent the movement or redeployment of enemy forces.
Deflecting: Preventing an enemy force from following the intended course.
Accident, traffic: An accident involving at least one motor vehicle.
Retain: Occupying and holding a terrain feature to ensure it is free of enemy occupation or use.
Naval platform flight operations: Aircraft launch or recovery by a naval platform.
Flood: The overflowing of a body of water onto dry land.
Communications restoration: The reestablishment of the ability to communicate.
Aircraft loss: The unforeseen loss of an aircraft (and personnel), other than crash.

Serving as a bridgehead force: Operating as a force that seizes or controls ground in order to permit the continuous embarkation, landing or crossing of troops or materiel and to provide manoeuvre space during a water obstacle crossing.
Procuring: Buying whatever is needed to fulfil a certain action.
Human rights violation: The commitment of an act against human rights.
Demolition: The destruction of structures, facilities, or materiel by use of fire, water, explosives, mechanical, or other means.
Bombing, accidental: An unfortunate bombing incident that happens unexpectedly and unintentionally.
Troublemaking, bullying: Intimidating by the use of superior size or strength.
Local election: An ACTION-EVENT in which local officials are selected by vote.
Patrolling: Gathering information or carrying out a destructive, harassing, mopping-up, or security mission.
Earthquake: A convulsion of the earths crust due to the release of accumulated stress as a result of faults in strata or volcanic action.
Clearing, air: Clearing of the air to gain either temporary or permanent air superiority or control in a given sector.
Atmospheric pollution: Contamination of the atmosphere caused by a poison or toxin.
Resting: Observing a specified period of inactivity by an organisation that is out of contact with the enemy.
Naval gun fire: The act of firing a naval surface-to-surface weapon.
Fix, electro-optical: Determining a position using electro-optical data.
Communications outage: The failure of communications equipment due to a mechanical malfunction.
Advancing: Moving towards an objective in some form of tactical formation. This is a transitional phase between operations that may or may not result in contact with the enemy.
Publishing media documentary: Making generally known any document published on a media that provides a factual record or report.
Troublemaking, hooliganism: Causing difficulties by the actions of hoodlums, especially young ruffians.
Looting: Act to take private property from an enemy in war or stolen by thieves.
Electronic emission: The radiation of electromagnetic energy.
Clearing, obstacle: Eliminating or neutralizing an obstacle.
Assassination: Murder of a prominent person.
Retire: Moving a force out of contact with the enemy with the expectation of no further significant contact.
Network seizure: Taking electronic control of a communications network.

Following and assuming: Operating as a committed force that is following a force conducting an offensive operation and is prepared to continue the mission of the force it is following when that force is fixed, attrited, or otherwise unable to continue.
Constructing: Building, digging or creating an object.
Accident, workplace: An accident occurring at the workplace.
Serving as a breakout force: Operating as a force that is tasked with the continuation of the operation during an obstacle crossing.
Protection, electronic: That division of electronic warfare involving actions taken to ensure effective friendly use of the electromagnetic spectrum despite the enemys use of electromagnetic energy.
Hostage taking: Action to seize or hold a person as security for the fulfilment of a condition.
Denying: Preventing access by blocking, disrupting, dislocating and/or bringing fire to bear.
Belly landing: An aircraft has landed without using the landing gear.
Troublemaking, harassing: Persecuting systematically by besetting with annoyances, threats or demands.
Locating: Establishing the position of an object.
Publishing media article: Making generally known a non-fictional essay, especially one included with others in a newspaper, magazine, journal, etc.
Early warning alert: Early notification of the launch or approach of weapons or weapons carriers.
Clearing, land combat: Removing all enemy forces from a specific location, area, or zone.
Assisting a criminal: Assisting or abetting a known criminal or terrorist.
Reinforcing: Making a force available for the purpose of supplementing an in-place force.
Explosion: A sudden release of any kind of energy.
Consolidating of a position: Re-organising and strengthening of a newly captured position so that it can be used against the enemy.
Codeword execution: Initiating the codeword activity.
War/military conference: A meeting of a group of persons to discuss war/military process.
Security violation: An infringement of a security protocol.
Peace conference: A meeting of a group of persons to discuss a peace process.

Deception, electronic: In electronic countermeasures, the deliberate radiation, re-radiation, alteration, absorption or reflection of electromagnetic energy in a manner intended to confuse, distract or seduce an enemy or his electronic systems.
Border crossing, forced: A border crossing that is conducted under pressure.
Supporting: Aiding, protecting, complementing or sustaining an object.
Providing repair services: Providing labour and materiel to restore objects to sound condition.

Isolation: Sealing off (both physically and psychologically) an enemy from its sources of support, denying an enemy freedom of movement, and preventing an enemy unit from having contact with other enemy forces.
Drug storage: An action to store drugs.
Arms trade: A happening of selling or buying of arms.
Refugee movement: The movement of people who has been forced to leave their country in order to escape war, persecution, or natural disaster.
Mission staging: The assembly of aircraft for the completion of a mission or other activity.
Execution: Putting a person to death, especially as a legal penalty.
Conducting rearward passage of lines: Moving a force through the defensive positions of another force behind it in order to break contact with the enemy.
Ceremony or parade: The formal gathering of a group of people in order to carry out an act or series of acts prescribed by ritual protocol or convention.
Abdication: The renouncement by a person of his official functions.
War/crisis alert: The state of readiness caused by the possibility of a war.
Surveillance, electronic: The systematic observation of aerospace, surface or subsurface areas, places, persons, or things, by electronic means.
Issuing media documentary: Sending forth or putting into circulation any document published on a media that provides a factual record or report.
Drought: A prolonged or chronic shortage of water.

Airborne assault: Mounting an airborne operation, a phase beginning with delivery by air of the assault echelon of the force into the objective area and extending through attack of assault objectives and consolidation of the initial airhead.
Religious demonstration: A public display of group feelings towards a religious idea, person or cause.
Mortar fire: The discharge of a projectile from a mortar weapon.

Exploitation: Taking advantage of a successful attack by mounting an offensive operation to follow-up and harass a dislocated enemy with the aim of further disorganising him in depth. This may provide the opportunity to capture ground that was not part of the objective of the original attack.
Collision, mid-air: In-flight collision of an aircraft with another aircraft.
CBRN-EVENT: An ACTION-EVENT that involves chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear materiel individually or in combination.
War crime: Violation of the laws and customs of war, i.e. the principles and norms of international law that enshrine the rights and duties of warring parties and neutral states.
Seizing: Clearing a designated area and obtaining control of it.
Penetrating: Breaking through the enemys defence or disrupting the enemys defensive systems.
Hijacking, not otherwise specified: Seizure of a vehicle in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Deception: Employing measures designed to mislead the enemy by manipulation, distortion, or falsification of evidence to induce him to react in a manner prejudicial to his interests.
Border crossing, escorted: A border crossing that is conducted under escort.
Surrender: Yielding to the control or power of the enemy.
Providing security services: Providing labour and materiel to assure safety of personnel and facilities.
Issuing media article: Sending forth or putting into circulation a non-fictional essay, especially one included with others in a newspaper, magazine, or journal.
Drug transportation: An action to transport drugs.
Arms production: An activity of, relating to or based on the production of arms.
Vessel sinking: The unforeseen loss, damage or destruction of a vessel by submersion.
Poisoning: Injuring or killing with toxic agents.
Hijacking, land vehicle: Seizure of a land vehicle in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Arresting/obstructing: Stopping or checking of the motion, progress, growth, or spread of something.
Suspension of hostilities: The cessation of war activities.
Providing storage services: Providing services for storage.
Issuing press release: Sending forth or putting into circulation an official statement issued to media for information.
Drive-by shooting: The act of firing a weapon, usually at a person, from a passing vehicle.
Accident: An unfortunate event, esp. one causing physical harm or damage, brought about unintentionally.
Civil demonstration, illegal: A public meeting or march illegally expressing protest or other opinion on an issue.
Religious violence: Individual or organised act directed against groups or individuals because of their religious beliefs.
Murder: The unlawful killing of one human being by another, especially with premeditated malice.
Famine: An extreme scarcity of food.
Collision, obstacle: In-flight collision of an aircraft with natural or man-made object (fixed or mobile) located on the ground.
Border crossing, planned: A border crossing that is known to have been planned ahead of time.
Oceans, seas or water pollution: Contamination of a body of water caused by a poison or toxin.
Shooting: The act of firing of a weapon, usually at a person.
Petroleum product spills: The accidental or delivered release of any petroleum product into the environment.
Hijacking, boat: Seizure of a boat or ship in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Death of chief of state: Self-defined.
Arson: The crime of maliciously setting fire to the property of another or of burning ones own property for an improper purpose, as to collect insurance.
Reorganising: Changing a task organisation for a particular operation. (Normally takes place before an operation). This includes the transfer of authority.
Natural disaster: The damage caused by force of nature, such as a hurricane, cyclone, tornado or tidal wave.
Fix: Preventing the enemy from moving any part of his force from a specific location for a specific period of time.
Communications deactivation: The disabling of transmission of information.
Border crossing, illegal: A border crossing that is forbidden by law.
Withdrawal: Disengaging a force in contact from an enemy force.
Sniper attack: An attack by one who shoots at others from a concealed place.
Political demonstration: A public display of group feelings towards a political idea, person or cause.
Hijacking, plane: Seizure of an aircraft in order to go somewhere other than the scheduled destination.
Defeat: Diminution of the effectiveness of the enemy to the extent that he is unable to participate further in the battle or at least cannot fulfil his intention.
Arresting, legal: Seizing and detaining of a person under authority of the law.

Terrorism: Using or threatening force or violence against individuals or property in an attempt to coerce or intimidate governments or societies to achieve political, religious or ideological objectives.
Providing transhipment services: Providing movement of cargo from one ship or train or container to another for further shipment.
Jamming: Deliberately radiating, re-radiating or reflecting electromagnetic energy with the object of impairing the use of electronic devices, equipment or systems being used by the enemy.

Disrupting: Breaking apart an enemys formation and tempo, interrupting the enemys time table, causing premature commitment of forces, and/or splintering their attack using integrated fire planning and obstacle effect.
Civil disobedience: The refusal to comply with certain laws or to pay taxes etc. as a peaceful form of political protest.
Accident, aircraft ground: An accident involving an aircraft during ground operations or maintenance.
Religious warfare: An act of open armed conflict due to a difference of religious belief between two separate groups.
Mutual assistance pact agreement: An arrangement or contract between a number of organisations to provide mutual support.
Fire: A rapid, persistent chemical reaction that releases heat and light, especially the exothermic combination of a combustible substance with oxygen.
Communications activation: The enabling of transmission of information.
Border crossing, not-planned: A border crossing that is unplanned.
Withdrawal under pressure: Disengaging from the enemy when the enemy has sufficient contact with friendly forces to interfere with the withdrawal.
